item.title: Router Corner Template (metric)
item.description:
I've been using hanselcj's awesome router corner templates for quite some time, but since I live in a country that uses the metric system I came upon a use case where I needed a metric size. My current project is to build a router table with a custom router plate. My plan is to use the template to trimm the edges of the plate. But in order to create a perfect fit with the trimm on the table the corner radius needs to fit the size of my router bit. So far I only created a 16mm template as I only plan on using a 16mm router bit. If you need a specific size though, just let me know and I'll create it.

If my design helped you please consider buying me a coffee or at least giving me a "like". That would really mean a lot to me and validate all the time spent creating free designs.

item.title: Carbonation Cap Kegerator Font
item.description:
Here we have a new interesting remix of two projects to take this idea into a new direction for pluto tap owners.
3x PCO 1881 (aka PET Bottle tops) are attached to a standard base for fits keg-king/mangrove-jacks kegerator fridge.
Diagonal measurement from centre to centre across the circumference mounting holes is 97mm.
This is designed to suit the PET Carbonation Caps that are cheap and easily mated to this unique tap head.
the kegerator owner could reasonably buy one Pluto gun, and swap the gun between kegs.
After the session concludes, the pluto gun is then returned to the fridge or cleaned for the next session.
Simply connect each carbonation cap to beer line and whatever keg disconnect type you use on your kegs.

https://www.google.com/search?q=carbonation+caps
https://www.google.com/search?q=pluto+gun
https://www.keg-king.com.au/s4-homebrew-pack.html

this model has been printed in both PETG and ABS, and i can personally confirm PETG is preferable. Finish quality and bed adhesion was more successful with PETG.
ABS was printed at 232C and 110c bed on an ender3 pro.
PETG was printed at 232c and 100c bed on an ender3 pro.

original projects in this remix;
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:3732085
thank you for the base sketch of the font >> https://www.thingiverse.com/omphteliba

https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:499261
Thank you for the PCO1881 insert used as a component (reposted here) >> https://www.thingiverse.com/jsc

Fusion 360 archive and active project for the collar
.STL's for aligning to your printer profile;

  • please print with support for the 1881 font as the PCO threads need to defy gravity.
  • print with wall thickness of 3mm
  • 15% cubic infill for the 1881 font
  • 25% lightning infill for the collar
  • layer thickness was 0.2mm on both models
  • use a brim on both models
    .gcode 'ready to go' load for instant Ender3 Print from TF.

good luck!

item.title: Rocinante USB Drive
item.description:
Remixed a remix of a remix to bring you a Rocinante USB thumb drive!

I used a Sandick Cruzer USB drive (https://www.amazon.ca/gp/product/B00NIEIRVY/ref=ppx_yo_dt_b_search_asin_title?ie=UTF8&psc=1) to make this.

Print on a RESIN printer, break the working bits out of the thumb drive plastic. Insert non-working end into engine part (will be a tight pressfit). Install 6x2mm magnets into holes on engine and rear body part. The magnets will stand proud on the engine part, and be recessed on the rear hull. This is BY DESIGN.

Super glue for everything, paint and done!

item.title: Bosch MUM4 disc axle
item.description:
This is the Bosch MuM4 series mixer/food processor's disc axle part. You need to have the original hexagonal shaft to assembly it.

I've created two versions as follows:

v1 is as close to the original as possible. Drawback is the brittle upper sticks (prone to break off from the original axle too)

v2 is without the upper sticks and the hexagonal shaft will get fixed to the disc axle with 5mm high hexagonal hole in the middle (this doesn't exist in the original Bosch part). When installing the hexa shaft, you need to push it in the middle hole until the first section of the shaft goes through the hexagonal hole, then turn the shaft 90degree and continue pushing into the final position. (The hexagonal shaft has 3 separated sections and the middle one is differs with 90deg.)

item.title: Mini FLSUN SR Super Racer Model
item.description:
I made a mini Sidewinder X1 and wanted a mini FLsun SR. I actually made this on the Q5 so I could measure on the SR while printing the prototype.

The struts should snap onto the effector plate and the carriers. Print a carrier and a strut first at .06 or .1 layer height to see if they snap together. if not scale the strut to fit. Print 3 Carriers and 6 struts then snap them together

Then print the Effector plate at .06 or .1 layer height but scale same as carriers. Snap struts onto it. If that works, print the top, bottom, 3 legs and the rest of the parts at .15 layer height. I didn't use supports on anything

I used TPU as the PTFE tube and coiled some TPU on a real PTFE tube then heated with a heat gun to get it to coil up.

Glue it together solid if you like.

I added Fusion 360 files so you genius cad people can make improvements. Please share if you do. I had fun. Hope you do too.

I printed Phil-A-Ment at 20% scale
